ile-based detection when the CWD repo is not the same as the files' repo.\n\n## Key Technical Decisions\n\n- **Fix in handler, not presets:** The bug is a handler-level routing decision. Each preset correctly reports CWD and file paths. Making presets aware of nested repos would add complexity to 11+ presets and violate separation of concerns.\n\n- **Reuse existing multi-repo path:** The file-based detection path (lines 660-841) already correctly groups files by repo and processes each repo independently. The fix should redirect to this path when needed, rather than adding a new code path.\n\n- **Detection strategy -- compare file repos to CWD repo:** After finding the repo at CWD, use `find_repository_for_file()` on the edited file paths to check if any file belongs to a different repo. If yes, switch to the multi-repo processing path.\n\n## Open Questions\n\n### Resolved During Planning\n\n- **Q: Does `find_repository_for_file()` correctly handle the nested case?** Yes. It walks up from the file path and finds `subrepo-1/.git/` before reaching `parentRepo/.git/`. It only skips submodule `.git` files (those containing `gitdir:` + `/modules/`), not standalone nested repos.\n\n- **Q: What if the agent doesn't provide file paths in the hook payload?** Some hook events (like a general \"session start\") may not include file paths. In those cases, the handler falls back to the CWD repo, which is the correct behavior -- there's nothing to re-route without file paths. The existing fallback is fine.\n\n- **Q: What about relative file paths?** The existing code at lines 674-687 already converts relative paths to absolute using `repository_working_dir`. This still works because even relative paths like `subrepo-1/src/foo.ts` resolve to the correct absolute path.\n\n### Deferred to Implementation\n\n- **Exact placement of the re-route check:** Whether to insert the check immediately after line 658 (before entering either branch) or after line 853 (at the start of single-repo mode). The former is cleaner but needs careful handling of the `repo_result` ownership.\n\n## Implementation Units\n\n- [ ] **Unit 1: Add nested-repo detection and re-routing in checkpoint handler**\n\n**Goal:** When the CWD resolves to a parent git repo, detect that edited files belong to nested subrepos and route checkpoints to the correct repos.\n\n**Requirements:** R1, R2, R3\n\n**Dependencies:** None\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `src/commands/git_ai_handlers.rs`\n- Test: `tests/integration/cross_repo_cwd_attribution.rs`\n\n**Approach:**\n\nAfter the current single-repo detection (line 653-658), add a check: if `repo_result.is_ok()` AND the agent provides explicit file paths (`edited_filepaths` or `will_edit_filepaths`), verify whether any file's `find_repository_for_file()` returns a different workdir than the CWD repo's workdir.\n\nIf any file maps to a different repo, set `needs_file_based_repo_detection = true` and fall through to the existing multi-repo processing path. The existing code at lines 660-841 already handles everything correctly from that point.\n\nKey detail: when re-routing, the file-based detection code at line 691 uses `repository_working_dir` as the workspace root for `group_files_by_repository()`. This should remain the agent's original CWD (the parent repo) so that relative path resolution still works correctly. No change needed here.\n\nAlso handle the case where SOME files belong to the CWD repo and others to nested repos (mixed edit) -- the multi-repo path already handles this correctly since `group_files_by_repository` will place each file in its correct repo.\n\n**Patterns to follow:**\n- The existing `needs_file_based_repo_detection` flag pattern\n- The `group_files_by_repository()` call at line 690-691\n- The `find_repository_for_file()` function\n\n**Test scenarios:**\n\nHappy path:\n- Agent CWD is parentRepo, edits one file in subrepo-1 -> checkpoint written to subrepo-1, `git-ai status` in subrepo-1 shows AI attribution\n- Agent CWD