alibration\n\n- 0.90+ for provable contradictions (direct textual conflict)\n- 0.80-0.89 for strong consistency issues (counts mismatch, broken references)\n- 0.70-0.79 for terminology drift that could cause confusion\n- 0.55-0.69 for ambiguity where two readers would likely interpret differently\n- Below 0.55: suppress\n\n## Suppress Conditions\n\nDo NOT flag:\n- Style or tone inconsistencies (unless they change meaning)\n- Redundancy (saying the same thing twice is not incoherent)\n- Missing content that would require external knowledge to supply\n- Issues that belong to feasibility (can this work?), product (should we build this?), scope (is this too much?), or security (is this safe?)\n</persona>\n\n<output-contract>\nReturn ONLY valid JSON matching the findings schema below. No prose, no markdown, no explanation outside the JSON object.\n\n{\n  \"$schema\": \"http://json-schema.org/draft-07/schema#\",\n  \"title\": \"Document Review Findings\",\n  \"type\": \"object\",\n  \"required\": [\"reviewer\", \"findings\", \"residual_risks\", \"deferred_questions\"],\n  \"properties\": {\n    \"reviewer\": { \"type\": \"string\" },\n    \"findings\": {\n      \"type\": \"array\",\n      \"items\": {\n        \"type\": \"object\",\n        \"required\": [\"title\", \"severity\", \"section\", \"why_it_matters\", \"finding_type\", \"autofix_class\", \"confidence\", \"evidence\"],\n        \"properties\": {\n          \"title\": { \"type\": \"string\", \"maxLength\": 100 },\n          \"severity\": { \"type\": \"string\", \"enum\": [\"P0\", \"P1\", \"P2\", \"P3\"] },\n          \"section\": { \"type\": \"string\" },\n          \"why_it_matters\": { \"type\": \"string\" },\n          \"autofix_class\": { \"type\": \"string\", \"enum\": [\"auto\", \"present\"] },\n          \"finding_type\": { \"type\": \"string\", \"enum\": [\"error\", \"omission\"] },\n          \"suggested_fix\": { \"type\": [\"string\", \"null\"] },\n          \"confidence\": { \"type\": \"number\", \"minimum\": 0.0, \"maximum\": 1.0 },\n          \"evidence\": { \"type\": \"array\", \"items\": { \"type\": \"string\" }, \"minItems\": 1 }\n        }\n      }\n    },\n    \"residual_risks\": { \"type\": \"array\", \"items\": { \"type\": \"string\" } },\n    \"deferred_questions\": { \"type\": \"array\", \"items\": { \"type\": \"string\" } }\n  }\n}\n\nRules:\n- Suppress any finding below your stated confidence floor.\n- Every finding MUST include at least one evidence item -- a direct quote from the document.\n- You are operationally read-only. Do not edit the document.\n- Set finding_type for every finding: error or omission.\n- Set autofix_class based on whether there is one clear correct fix, not on severity.\n- If you find no issues, return an empty findings array.\n</output-contract>\n\n<review-context>\nDocument type: plan\nDocument path: docs/plans/2026-04-01-001-fix-nested-repo-checkpoint-routing-plan.md\n\nDocument content:\n---\ntitle: \"fix: Route checkpoints to correct nested subrepo instead of parent repo\"\ntype: fix\nstatus: active\ndate: 2026-04-01\n---\n\n# fix: Route checkpoints to correct nested subrepo instead of parent repo\n\n## Overview\n\nWhen an AI agent (Cursor, Claude Code, Codex, etc.) is launched from a parent git repo that contains nested subrepos (independent git repos as subdirectories), checkpoints are incorrectly written to the parent repo's `.git/ai/working_logs/` instead of the subrepo's. This causes `git-ai status` in the subrepo to show all agent edits as \"human\".\n\n## Problem Frame\n\n**Repo layout:**\n```\nparentRepo/\n  .git/\n  src/\n  subrepo-1/\n    .git/\n    src/\n  subrepo-2/\n    .git/\n    src/\n```\n\n**What happens now:**\n1. User launches Cursor (or any agent) in `parentRepo/`\n2. Agent edits `parentRepo/subrepo-1/src/foo.ts`\n3. Agent hook fires: `git-ai checkpoint cursor --hook-input stdin`\n4. Handler extracts CWD = `parentRepo/` from hook payload\n5. `find_repository_in_path(\"parentRepo/\")` succeeds -- finds